    <div class="container">
      <!-- Main component for a primary marketing message or call to action -->
      <div class="jumbotron">
        <h1><%= title %></h1>
        <p id="description">Last.ichecked is an app built using Last.fm's API. It currently uses the getTopArtists endpoint to get the 50 most subscribed artists on Last.fm.</p>
        <p>The last time that I checked, that API is public and serves more than just social data. If that ever changes, you won't be able to see a bar graph on the home page.</p>

        <p>EDIT: The API was bugging out on me, but Last.fm responded to my ticket and fixed this issue:</p>
        <a href="/images/lastfm_bug.png">
          <img class="bug" src="/images/lastfm_bug.png" width="400" alt="">
        </a>
        <a href="/images/lastfm_example.png">
          <img class="bug" src="/images/lastfm_example.png" width="400" alt="">
        </a>
        <p>I could use tag info to get descriptions of the genres that artists are tagged with.</p>

        <p>This site is currently not responsive, although that <a href="http://eyeseast.github.io/visible-data/2013/08/28/responsive-charts-with-d3/">can be implemented</a>. The link for the implementation uses Census data to find the percentage of citizens with at least a bachelor's degree, by state. I originally conceived of my final project as a mashup of Meetup API city data with other data that shows city trends based on more general demographic criteria. I'm starting to think, now, that I can use Census data for that.</p>

        <h3>Stretch goals and inspirations: </h3>
        <p>I'd like to run through the whole list of associated genres for a given artist and log the deviations that data holds from sets of data months or years before it. I also want to get lat/lon coordinates for where users who tag are located so that I can find out where genre association for a given artist is concentrated. (e.g. who recognizes chillwave hip-hop as chillwave, and not just hip-hop, and how does this look globally?)</p>
      </div>
